properties.name: Site--Hampton University
properties.description:
Land originally Tabb Farm and Little Scotland Plantation. Education began at the site during the Civil War, when several small schools (including the Butler School and a primary school in the cellar of Villa Margaret, operated by Peter Herbert) educated "Contraband" slaves in the area. In 1867, The American Missionary Association formally consolidated the schools and acquired nearby land to establish the Hampton Normal and Agricultural Institute, which opened in 1868 to teach former slaves to become educators or learn agricultural or trade skills. It became Hampton Institute in 1930 and Hampton University in 1984.
